english:
  title: Inscribed on a Landscape Painting
  author: Kang Hui-an
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The immortal mountain rises dense and towering,
    Its clouded breath connecting Penglai and Yingzhou.
    A thatched pavilion hides beneath the rocks,
    Green bamboo circles the eaves and pillars.

    A refined scholar plays the green-stringed lute,
    Its delicate notes harmonizing with the clear pine wind.
    When the ancient melody is complete,
    One awakens suddenly to the way of eternal life.

    Mountain peaks stand sharp and precipitous,
    Waterfalls pour forth like the celestial river.
    Spraying and surging ten thousand lengths high,
    Yet we can only gaze—never dwell there.

    Who is that wanderer upon the donkey?
    Even at arm's length, he hesitates and stumbles.
    At one long whistle, turning his head about,
    He finds heaven and earth are but a roadside inn.
  footnotes:
    - Penglai and Yingzhou are legendary paradises in Chinese mythology, often depicted in landscape paintings as islands of immortals.
    - The green-stringed lute (Luqi) is a classical Chinese instrument associated with refinement and spiritual cultivation.
    - The 'ancient melody' suggests music predating civilization itself, connecting the player to primordial harmony.
    - The final image transforms the mystical landscape into something ordinary—suggesting that enlightenment reveals the illusory nature of spiritual seeking.
